==English==
===Etymology===
From Old English [[gigawe]], [[gugawe]], [[gewgaude]]; probably the same word as Old Englihs [[givegove]] gewgaw, apparently a reduplicated form from Anglo Saxon [[gifan]], to give; compare also French [[joujou]], plaything, and E. [[gaud]]

===Pronunciation===
gew"gaw 
*{{audio|en-us-gewgaw.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Adjective===
'''gewgaw'''
#[[showy|Showy]]; [[unreal]]; [[pretentious]].
#:''Seeing his '''gewgaw''' castle shine."'' &mdash;Tennyson.

===Noun===
#A [[showy]] [[trifle]]; a toy; a splendid [[plaything]]; a pretty but [[worthless]] [[bauble]].
#:''"A heavy '''gewgaw''' called a crown."'' &mdash;Dryden.


